English Summary

55.3% Increase in Exports or -12.2% Reduction? Structural Changes in Armenias Trade

The 2023 Export Study by Partners reveals a substantial 55.3 percent increase in Armenias exports, reaching $8.4 billion, with a parallel 40.2 percent surge in imports to $12.3 billion. Notably, a significant portion of the export growth, 31 percent or $2.6 billion, occurred in the last two months of the year, marking a historical moment as Armenias exports surpassed imports in December 2023. However, a deeper analysis unveils a nuanced realityexcluding Russia, the UAE, and Hong Kong from the trade cycle results in a concerning 12.2 percent reduction in exports to other countries, challenging the assumption of stable export growth.

The geographical concentration of exports is noteworthy, with 75 percent directed to Russia, the UAE, and Hong Kong in 2023. Despite an overall positive trajectory in trade turnover, the negative trend in exports to other destinations raises concerns, hinting at a potential contraction in both import and export activities to non-core countries in the upcoming year.
